docs.lead_paragraph: SUICIDE BY AN ENGLISH SURGEON--POVERTY AND DESPAIR--Yesterday morning, Coroner GAMBLE was called to hold an inquest at the Sixth Ward Station-house, on the body of WALTER JARDINE, an English Surgeon, aged 35 years, who committed suicide in the rear of No. 135 Walker-street.

headline.main: The Release of Captain Gray.; To the Editor of the New-York Daily Times:

docs.lead_paragraph: Captain GRAY, of this city, who sold the Lady Suffolk to some of your New-Yorkers, who it is alleged, with certain parties in Cuba, have put her into the slave trade, has been fully discharged, and is now on his way home in the steamer Isabel, via Charleston.

docs.lead_paragraph: TELEGRAPH LINES IN CUBA.--The Government of Cuba recently advertised for proposals for laying down six hundred miles of subtorranean telegraph wires, and also for building three hundred miles upon posts, after the manner of the lines in the United States.

docs.lead_paragraph: THE ZEBRA AGAIN.--We are pleased to learn from the consigness, Messrs. KINCHLEY, LOCKETT Co., that Dr. DEMERE returned from the above vessel last night, and reports the health of the emigrants greatly improved. No new cases have occurred for two days, and the general appearance of the sufferers greatly improved.

docs.lead_paragraph: In pursuance of a call, published yesterday morning, and signed by Mayor WESTERVELT and several distinguished citizens, a meeting was held in the Astor House, last evening, to take measures for the relief of the unfortunate sufferers in Madeira, who had been rendered destitute by the failure of the Vine and Potato.
